{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471567"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"375"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/375"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.21,0.08,0.6,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96632"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/375"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79266"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2467"},{"type":"tags","id":"6198"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1150"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33129"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96632"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the hospital for delivery at 38 weeks gestation. She gives birth to a male infant with no complications during delivery. She reports smoking five to 10 cigarettes daily throughout the pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the neonate appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The neonatal examination on day one reveals bilateral foot deformities with inward and downward pointing feet that cannot be passively corrected (Image). There are no other dysmorphic features, and examination of the cardiovascular, respiratory and neurological systems are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Achilles tenotomy","Boots and bar","No management required","Serial casting","Triple arthrodesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with the classic appearance of congenital talipes equinovarus (clubfoot), which is characterised by a complex deformity involving forefoot adduction, midfoot supination, hindfoot varus, and ankle equinus. The inability to passively correct the deformity indicates this is a fixed rather than positional deformity, requiring active intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerial casting\u003C/strong\u003E using the Ponseti method is the gold standard initial management for congenital talipes equinovarus. This technique involves weekly gentle manipulation and casting, typically starting within the first few weeks of life. The Ponseti method has revolutionised clubfoot treatment, with success rates of over 90% when properly applied.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchilles tenotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is often required as part of the Ponseti protocol, but it is performed after several weeks of serial casting when the forefoot adduction and hindfoot varus have been corrected but equinus deformity persists. It is not the initial management approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoots and bar\u003C/strong\u003E (foot abduction orthosis) are used after the casting phase is complete to maintain the correction achieved. This typically involves wearing the orthosis full-time for three months, followed by night-time and nap-time wear until age 4-5 years. This is a crucial part of treatment but follows the initial casting phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo management required\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as untreated clubfoot leads to significant disability, pain, and abnormal gait. Early intervention is essential for optimal outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriple arthrodesis\u003C/strong\u003E is a salvage surgical procedure for older children or adults with residual or recurrent deformity. It involves fusion of the subtalar, calcaneocuboid, and talonavicular joints. This invasive procedure is not appropriate as initial management for a neonate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaternal smoking during pregnancy, as noted in this case, is a recognised risk factor for clubfoot. Other risk factors include family history, male gender, and oligohydramnios. The condition may be isolated or associated with other conditions such as arthrogryposis or neural tube defects, though in this case, no other abnormalities were detected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Maternal smoking during pregnancy is a risk factor for congenital talipes equinovarus (club foot).","The Ponseti method for congenital talipes equinovarus (club foot) involves sequential casting followed by bracing to maintain correction."],"references":["Chen C, Kaushal N, Scher DM, Doyle SM, Blanco JS, Dodwell ER. Clubfoot Etiology: A Meta-Analysis and Systematic Review of Observational and Randomized Trials. J Pediatr Orthop. 2018 Sep;38(8):e462-e469. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29917009/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79266"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"375"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18472"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18472"},"attributes